<subsection xml:id="subsec-laws-of-indices">
    <title>Laws of Indices</title>
    <p>
        To work with indices efficiently, we use a set of rules called the Laws of Indices.
    </p>
    <p>
        <term>a) Product Law</term>
    </p>
    <p>
        When multiplying numbers with the same base, add their powers.
    </p>
    <p>
        i.e <me> a^m</me> \times <me>a^n</me> = <me>a^(mn)</me>
    </p>
    <p>
        <term>Example:</term>
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>3^2 \times 3^4</m> = <m>3^(2 + 4)</m> = <m>3^6</m>
    </p>

    <p>
        <term>b) Quotient Law</term>
    </p>
    <p>
        When dividing numbers with the same base, subtract their powers.
    </p>
    <p>
        i.e <me> \frac {a^m}{a^n}</me> = <me>a^(m-n)</me>
    </p>
    <p>
        <term>Example:</term>
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\frac {5^7}{5^3} </m> = <m>5^(7 - 3)</m> = <m>5^4</m>
    </p>

    <p>
        <term>c) Power of a Power Law</term>
    </p>
    <p>
        When raising a power to another power, multiply the powers.
    </p>
    <p>
        i.e <me>(a^m)^n</me> = <me>a^(m \times n)</me>
    </p>
    <p>
        <term>Example:</term>
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>(2^3)^2</m> = <m>2^(3 \times 2)</m> = <m>2^6</m>
    </p>

    <p>
        <term>d) Zero Exponent(Power Zero) Law</term>
    </p>
    <p>
        Any number raised to the power of zero is always 1.
    </p>
    <p>
        i.e <me>(a^0)</me> = <me>1</me>
    </p>
    <p>
        <term>Note</term>
    </p>
    <p>
        For the Power Law, <m>a</m> nq <m>0</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        <term>Example:</term>
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>7^0</m> = <m>1</m>
    </p>

    <p>
        <term>e) Negative power Law</term>
    </p>
    <p>
        A negative power means taking the reciprocal.
    </p>
    <p>
        i.e <me>a^(-n)</me> = <me>\frac {1}{a^n}</me>
    </p>
    <p>
        <term>Example:</term>
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>4^-2</m> = <m>\frac {1}{4^2}</m> = <m>\frac {1}{16}</m>
    </p>

    <p>
        <term>f) Fractional Powers</term>
    </p>
    <p>
        A fractional power represents a root.
    </p>
    <p>
        i.e <me>(a^(\frac {m}{n}))</me> = <me> \sqrt [n]{a^m}</me>
    </p>
    <p>
        <term>Example:</term>
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>8^(\frac {1}{3})</m> = <m>\sqrt [3]{8^1}</m> = <m>2</m>
    </p>

    <p>
        <term>Important</term>
    </p>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The laws apply only when the bases are the same
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>

</subsection>